addr="dummit-2004-abstract"
title="Abstract Algebra">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Section 14.1</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-000J.xml"
addr="nt-000J"
title="Degree of extension">finite extension</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> is said to be <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Galois</html:dfn> if
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[|\mathop {\textrm {Aut}}\nolimits (\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F})| = [\Bbbk  : \mathbb {F}].]]></fr:tex>
In that case, we write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {Aut}}\nolimits (\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex>, and it is called the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Galois Group of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex></html:dfn>.</fr:p><fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)\in \mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-0025.xml"
addr="nt-0025"
title="Separable Polynomial">separable</fr:link> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-001S.xml"
addr="nt-001S"
title="Splitting Field of a Polynomial">splitting field</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex> is called the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Galois Group of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex></html:dfn>.</fr:p>
 
   
